1. What is the signature of the main() method in Java?
-->👉 The standard signature is:
public static void main(String[] args)
👉 You can also write:
public static void main(String... args) // varargs



2. Why is main() declared as public static void ?
-->public → JVM can access it from anywhere
static → No object needed to call it
void → Does not return anything to JVM


3. Can we overload the main() method? If yes, how does Java determine which main() to call?
-->👉 Yes, we can overload it ✅

Example
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Original main");
        main(10);
    }

    public static void main(int x) {
        System.out.println("Overloaded main: " + x);
    }
}

👉 Output:

Original main
Overloaded main: 10
🔥 Important:

👉 JVM only calls:

public static void main(String[] args)






4. Can the main() method be private or protected?
-->👉 ❌ No

JVM must access it from outside the class
So it must be public


5. Explain what happens when a Java program does not contain a main() method?
-->👉 Program compiles ✔️
👉 But runtime error ❌

Example error:

Error: Main method not found





6. Explain why main() must be static?Can we change the order of keywords like static, public?
-->👉 JVM calls main() without creating object

🔹 Keyword order

👉 ✔️ Order can be changed:

static public void main(String[] args)

👉 ❌ But best practice:

public static void main(String[] args)



7. Can we have multiple main() methods in different classes?
-->👉 ✅ Yes, allowed

class A {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Class A");
    }
}

class B {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Class B");
    }
}
👉 You choose which class to run.



8. Can main() throw exceptions? If yes, which types?
-->👉 ✅ Yes

Example
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        throw new Exception("Error");
    }
}

👉 It can throw:

Checked exceptions (Exception, IOException)
Unchecked exceptions (RuntimeException)
